<BaseLayout title="Methodology | LetsFixIndia" description="How LetsFixIndia separates events, evidence, allegations, outcomes, and corrections.">
  <div class="page-shell"><header class="record-header"><p class="eyebrow">Method</p><h1>A record earns trust by showing its working.</h1><p class="lede">This is a public record, not a verdict. Its job is to make claims, evidence, outcomes, and uncertainty easy to distinguish.</p></header>
    <div class="method-grid section">
      <article class="method-card"><p class="eyebrow">01</p><h3>Start with a named source</h3><p>Every public entry should point to an official document, court record, credible reporting, or other checkable source.</p></article>
      <article class="method-card"><p class="eyebrow">02</p><h3>Keep claims proportional</h3><p>An allegation stays an allegation. A reported event, a court finding, and a final outcome are not interchangeable.</p></article>
      <article class="method-card"><p class="eyebrow">03</p><h3>Show uncertainty</h3><p>Missing URLs and unresolved questions are marked so readers can see the limits of an entry.</p></article>
      <article class="method-card"><p class="eyebrow">04</p><h3>Accept correction</h3><p>A stronger source, a corrected date, or a later legal outcome should improve the record—not get buried.</p></article>
    </div>
    <section class="section"><div class="callout"><p><strong>Editorial independence:</strong> support, disagreement, or popularity do not decide an entry. Evidence and clear wording do.</p></div></section>
    <section class="section civic-note"><p class="eyebrow">Civic premise</p><h2>Democracy asks more of citizens than attention.</h2><p>It depends on people being able to find public information, distinguish evidence from assertion, and revise their views when the record changes. LetsFixIndia exists to make that work less difficult.</p></section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
